<!-- WHY THIS AREA -->
<section style="background:var(--color-base, #f2efe9); padding:80px 24px;">
  <div style="max-width:800px; margin:0 auto;">
    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:0.75rem; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:0.15em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#c4912a; margin-bottom:1rem;">Local Expertise</p>
    <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif); font-size:clamp(1.8rem, 3.5vw, 2.8rem); font-weight:300; line-height:1.2; color:#1c1917; margin-bottom:1.75rem;">The honest inner south: five kilometres from the CBD, genuine affordability, and a buyer market that has been quietly growing for several years.</h2>
    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      Moorooka is in postcode 4105, five kilometres south of the CBD on the Ipswich Road corridor, with frequent bus services delivering a practical commute to the city centre. The suburb borders Annerley to the north, Woolloongabba to the northeast, Rocklea to the south and Salisbury to the southeast. It does not have its own train station, but the Ipswich Road bus connection is well-used and Rocklea station is accessible. The housing stock runs from original Queenslanders on established lots through to post-war brick homes and a growing supply of townhouses near the commercial corridors. Parts of the suburb near the industrial fringe are in a clear transition, with residential development and gentrification following investor interest that arrived ahead of the family owner-occupier market.
    </p>
<!-- APPRAISAL FORM -->
<div style="background:#fff; border-left:4px solid #c4912a; padding:2rem 2rem 1.75rem; margin:2rem 0;">
